definitions.definition: To change place or posture ; to go , in any manner, from one place or position to another.
examples: I was sitting on the sofa for a long time, feeling too lazy to move .

definitions.definition: To act ; to take action ; to begin to act
examples: Come on guys, let's move : there's work to do!

definitions.definition: To change residence , for example from one house, town, or state, to another; to go and live at another place. See also move out and move in .
examples: I decided to move to the country for a more peaceful life.
They moved closer to work to cut down commuting time.
I'm moving next week but I don't have anything packed yet.

definitions.definition: To cause to change place or posture in any manner; to set in motion ; to carry , convey , draw , or push from one place to another
examples: The waves moved the boat up and down.

definitions.definition: To transfer (a piece) from one space or position on the board to another.
examples: She moved the queen closer to the centre of the board.
He rolled a 5 and moved his counter to Boardwalk, the most expensive property on the Monopoly board.

definitions.definition: To excite to action by the presentation of motives ; to rouse by representation , persuasion , or appeal ; to influence .
examples: This song moves me to dance.

definitions.definition: To arouse the feelings or passions of; especially, to excite to tenderness or compassion , to excite (for example, an emotion ).
To propose ; to recommend ; specifically, to propose formally for consideration and determination , in a deliberative assembly ; to submit
examples: I move to repeal the rule regarding obligatory school uniform.

definitions.definition: To mention ; to raise (a question); to suggest (a course of action); to lodge (a complaint).
To incite , urge (someone to do something); to solicit (someone for or of an issue); to make a proposal to.
To apply to, as for aid .
To request an action from the court .
examples: An attorney moved the court to issue a restraining order.
The district attorney moved for a non-suit.

definitions.definition: To bow or salute upon meeting .
To sell or market (especially physical inventory or illicit drugs ).
examples: This business will fail if it can't move the inventory quickly.

definitions.definition: To transfer the value of one object in memory to another efficiently (i.e., without copying it in entirety).
